{"title_page": "Dark Waters (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 American legal thriller film directed by Todd Haynes}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dark Waters\n| image          = Dark Waters poster.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Todd Haynes]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n* [[Christine Vachon]]\n* Pamela Koffler\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Mario Correa\n* [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n}}\n| based_on       = {{based on|\"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\"|[[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Ruffalo\n* [[Anne Hathaway]]\n* [[Tim Robbins]]\n* [[Bill Camp]]\n* [[Victor Garber]]\n* [[Mare Winningham]]\n* [[Bill Pullman]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[Marcelo Zarvos]]\n| cinematography = [[Edward Lachman]]\n| editing        = [[Affonso Gon\u00e7alves]]\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Participant (company)|Participant]]\n* [[Killer Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 126 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amctheatres.com/movies/dark-waters-61544 |title=Dark Waters |publisher=[[AMC Theatres]] |access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20 million\n| gross          = $21 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkwaters.htm |title=Dark Waters (2019) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]. [[IMDb]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Dark Waters''''' is a 2019 American [[legal thriller]] film directed by [[Todd Haynes]] and written by Mario Correa and [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]. The story dramatizes [[Robert Bilott]]'s case against the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]] after they contaminated a town with unregulated chemicals. It stars [[Mark Ruffalo]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]].\n\nThe film is based on the 2016 ''[[The New York Times Magazine|New York Times Magazine]]'' article \"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\" by [[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rich|first=Nathaniel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/the-lawyer-who-became-duponts-worst-nightmare.html|title=The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare|date=January 6, 2016|work=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|access-date=November 5, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143157/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/the-lawyer-who-became-duponts-worst-nightmare.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|issn=0362-4331|authorlink=Nathaniel Rich (novelist)}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 9, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143206/https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Parts of the story were also reported by Mariah Blake, whose 2015 article \"Welcome to Beautiful Parkersburg, West Virginia\" was a National Magazine Award finalist,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/business-news/media/national-magazine-awards-ellies-asme-finalists-2016-revealed-10314630-10314630/|title=American Society of Magazine Editors Unveils Finalists for 2016 National Magazine Awards|last=Steigrad|first=Alexandra|date=January 14, 2016|website=WWD|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143132/https://wwd.com/business-news/media/national-magazine-awards-ellies-asme-finalists-2016-revealed-10314630-10314630/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> and Sharon Lerner, whose series \"Bad Chemistry\" ran in ''[[The Intercept]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/|title=Bad Chemistry|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=October 24, 2019|website=[[The Intercept]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402142717/https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2015/08/11/dupont-chemistry-deception/|title=The Teflon Toxin: DuPont and the Chemistry of Deception|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=August 11, 2015|website=[[The Intercept]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://perma.cc/89PM-XBGW|archive-date=February 25, 2015|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Bilott also wrote a memoir, ''Exposure'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/exposurepoisoned0000bilo|title=Exposure: poisoned water, corporate greed, and one lawyer's twenty-year battle against DuPont |last=Bilott|first=Robert|date=2019 |location=New York |publisher=Atria Books |via=The Internet Archive}}</ref> detailing his 20-year legal battle against DuPont.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/9840cbc08c9048cc900f90bd1bd7fb4a|title=Lawyer who took on DuPont has book coming out|date=July 10, 2019|website=Associated Press News|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402143821/https://apnews.com/9840cbc08c9048cc900f90bd1bd7fb4a|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> \n\n''Dark Waters'' was theatrically released in a limited capacity on November 22, 2019, by [[Focus Features]], and went wide on December 6, 2019. The film received positive reviews from critics and has grossed $21 million.\n\n== Plot ==\n[[Robert Bilott]] is a corporate defense lawyer from [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] working for law firm [[Taft Stettinius & Hollister]]. Farmer Wilbur Tennant, who knows Robert's grandmother, asks Robert to investigate a number of unexplained deaths in [[Parkersburg, West Virginia]]. Tennant connects the deaths to the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]], and gives Robert a large case of videotapes.\n\nRobert visits the Tennants' farm, where he learns that 190 cattle have died with unusual medical conditions such as bloated organs, blackened teeth, and tumors. DuPont attorney Phil Donnelly tells him he is not aware of the case but will help out in any way he can. Robert files a small suit so he can gain information through [[legal discovery]] of the chemicals dumped on the site. When he finds nothing useful in the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] report, he realizes the chemicals might not be regulated by the EPA.\n\nRobert confronts Phil at an industry event, leading to an angry exchange. DuPont sends Robert hundreds of boxes, hoping to bury the evidence. Robert finds numerous references to PFOA, a chemical with no references in any medical textbook. In the middle of the night, Robert's pregnant wife Sarah finds him tearing the carpet off the floors and going through their pans. He has discovered that PFOA is [[perfluorooctanoic acid]], used to manufacture [[Teflon]] and used in American homes for nonstick pans. DuPont has been running tests of the effect of PFOA for decades, finding that it causes cancer and birth defects, but did not make the findings public. They dumped hundreds of gallons of toxic sludge upriver from Tennant's farm. PFOA and similar compounds are [[Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances#Forever chemicals|forever chemicals]], chemicals that do not leave the blood stream [[Bioaccumulation|and slowly accumulate]].\n\nTennant has been shunned by the community for suing their biggest employer, and he and his wife both have cancer. Robert encourages him to accept DuPont's settlement, but Tennant refuses, wanting justice. He tells Robert he and his wife both have cancer. Robert sends the DuPont evidence to the EPA and Department of Justice, among others. The EPA fines DuPont $16.5 million.\n\nRobert, however, is not satisfied; he realizes that the residents of Parkersburg will suffer the effects of the PFOA for the rest of their lives. He seeks [[Monitoring (medicine)|medical monitoring]] for all residents of Parkersburg in one large [[Class action|class-action lawsuit]]. However, DuPont sends a letter notifying residents of the presence of PFOA, thus starting the [[statute of limitations]] and giving any further action only a month to begin.\n\nSince PFOA is not regulated, Robert's team argues that the corporation is liable, as the amount in the water was higher than the one part per billion deemed safe by DuPont's internal documents. In court, DuPont claims their later study found that 150 parts per billion is safe. The locals protest and the story becomes national news. DuPont agrees to settle for $70 million. As DuPont is only required to carry out medical monitoring if scientists prove that PFOA causes the ailments, an independent scientific review is set up. To get data for it, DuPont tells the locals they can get their settlement money after donating blood. Nearly 70,000 people donate to the study.\n\nSeven years pass with no result from the study. Tennant dies and Robert becomes destitute following several pay cuts, straining his marriage. When Tom tells him he needs to take another pay cut, Robert collapses, shaking. Doctors tell Sarah he suffered an [[ischemia]], brought on by stress. Sarah tells Tom to stop making Robert feel like a failure, since he is doing something for people who need help.\n\nThe scientific review contacts Robert and tells him that PFOA causes multiple cancers and other diseases. At dinner with his family, Robert is informed that DuPont is reneging on the entire agreement. Robert decides to take each defendant's case to DuPont, one at a time. He wins the first three multimillion-dollar settlements against DuPont, and DuPont settles the class action for $671 million.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] as [[Robert Bilott]]\n* [[Anne Hathaway]] as Sarah Bilott\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as Tom Terp\n* [[Bill Camp]] as Wilbur Tennant \n* [[Victor Garber]] as Phil Donnelly\n* [[Mare Winningham]] as Darlene Kiger\n* [[Bill Pullman]] as Harry Deitzler\n* [[William Jackson Harper]] as James Ross\n* [[Louisa Krause]] as Karla\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nOn September 21, 2018, it was announced that [[Todd Haynes]] would direct the film, then titled ''Dry Run'', from a script by [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], which would be produced by [[Participant (company)|Participant Media]] along with [[Mark Ruffalo]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/carol-todd-haynes-direct-dry-run-participant-media-1202469279/|title='Carol' Helmer Todd Haynes To Direct 'Dry Run' Drama For Participant Media|date=September 21, 2018|access-date=September 22, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144115/https://deadline.com/2018/09/carol-todd-haynes-direct-dry-run-participant-media-1202469279/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> In November 2018, Ruffalo was officially set to star in the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/mark-ruffalo-confirmed-participant-media-todd-haynes-dupont-drama-movie-1202498626/|title=Mark Ruffalo To Star In Participant Media's Todd Haynes Pic About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=November 9, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144302/https://deadline.com/2018/11/mark-ruffalo-confirmed-participant-media-todd-haynes-dupont-drama-movie-1202498626/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]] joined the cast of the film, with [[Christine Vachon]] and Pamela Koffler producing under their [[Killer Films]] banner.<ref name=\"MoreCast\">{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal|last=Wiseman|first=Andreas|date=January 9, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144355/https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] began on January 14, 2019, in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"MoreCast\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://local12.com/news/local/shooting-for-film-starring-mark-ruffalo-anne-hathaway-begins-in-hamilton-monday|title=Shooting for film starring Mark Ruffalo, Anne Hathaway begins in Hamilton Monday|last=\"WKRC\"|date=January 11, 2019|website=Local12.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144422/https://local12.com/news/local/shooting-for-film-starring-mark-ruffalo-anne-hathaway-begins-in-hamilton-monday|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film was released in limited theatres on November 22, 2019, before going wide on December 6, 2019.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/|title=\u2018Dark Waters\u2019 Leads Tepid Arthouse Openers at Crowded Box Office|last=Brueggemann|first=Tom|date=November 27, 2019|website=[[Indiewire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144435/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Dark Waters'' grossed $11.1 million in the United States and Canada, and $9.9 million in other countries, for a worldwide total of $21 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n\nIn its opening weekend the film made $102,656 from four theaters, a per-venue average of $25,651.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> It expanded to 94 theaters the following weekend, making $630,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/|title='Harriet,' 'Jojo Rabbit,' and 'Parasite' Reap Holiday Box Office Bounty|last=Brueggemann|first=Tom|date=December 1, 2019|website=[[IndieWire]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144741/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 1, 2019}}</ref> The film went wide in its third weekend of release, making $4.1 million from 2,012 theaters, and then made $1.9 million in its fourth weekend.<ref name=\"expand\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|title=\u2018Frozen 2\u2019 Leads Dreary December Weekend With $34M+, \u2018Playmobil\u2019 Plunges To $670K \u2013 Sunday Update|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 8, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144822/https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/jumanji-the-next-level-richard-jewell-black-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202808689/|title=\u2018Jumanji: The Next Level\u2019 Advancing To $51M+ Opening; \u2018Richard Jewell\u2019 & \u2018Black Christmas\u2019 Earn Lumps Of Coal|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 15, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144821/https://deadline.com/2019/12/jumanji-the-next-level-richard-jewell-black-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202808689/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 90% based on 197 reviews, with an average rating of 7.3/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''Dark Waters'' powerfully relays a real-life tale of infuriating malfeasance, honoring the victims and laying blame squarely at the feet of the perpetrators.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_waters_2019/|title=Dark Waters (2019)|date=December 6, 2019|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402144827/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_waters_2019|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 72 out of 100, based on 36 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-waters|title=Dark Waters Reviews|date=November 22, 2019|website=Metacritic|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145211/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-waters|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 3.5 out of 5 stars, with 60% saying they would definitely recommend it to a friend.<ref name=expand/>\n\n=== Economic response ===\nThe DowDuPont breakup earlier in the year spun off a new DuPont company that continued to lose value throughout the second half of 2019 as investors grew concerned about the potential liabilities related to the old DuPont's fluoropolymer products. When ''Dark Waters'' was released on November 12, DuPont's stock price dropped even further by 7.15 points from 72.18 to 65.03. While the portfolio is now a part of [[Chemours]] and the companies settled the public health lawsuits referenced in the film, Chemours sued DuPont, alleging that the former parent company saddled it with onerous liabilities when it failed to prepare financial projections in good faith. Chemours estimated that it would need to pay over $200 million to address environmental damages in North Carolina caused by another PFAS manufacturing facility in that region. (The prior settlement in both West Virginia and Ohio cost $671 million, which was split between the two companies.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/01/09/heres-why-dupont-fell-405-in-2019.aspx|title=Here's Why DuPont Fell 40.5% in 2019|last=Chatsko|first=Maxx|date=January 9, 2020|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145208/https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/01/09/heres-why-dupont-fell-405-in-2019.aspx|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuPont CEO Marc Doyle, executives, and investors argued in internal statements that much of the movie was not based in fact and DuPont was misconstrued to fit the role of the enemy. According to Doyle, limited public statements were made because \u201cin a situation like this, it just doesn\u2019t do you much good to fight it out in the public eye. That would just drive more and more attention to it.\u201d Executive chairman Ed Breen wouldn\u2019t comment on whether DuPont would take legal action in response to the movie, but he did tell investors, \u201cObviously, we have a lot of legal folks [that] have been looking at this.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/dupont-execs-react-to-villain-role-in-dark-waters-film/|title=DuPont execs react to villain role in \u2018Dark Waters\u2019 film|last=Eichmann|first=Mark|date=November 1, 2019|website=whyy.org|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145229/https://whyy.org/articles/dupont-execs-react-to-villain-role-in-dark-waters-film/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Many of the executives with whom this movie draws fault still work, or recently worked at DuPont. 3M saw little to no change in its stock price the day of the film's release, but it was already experiencing a \"difficult year\" from \"potential liabilities due to possible litigation over previous production of PFAS.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/12/18/is-3m-stock-a-buy-for-2020.aspx|title=Is 3M Stock a Buy for 2020? The industrial giant had a very difficult 2019, but is it set for a turnaround in the coming year?|last=Samaha|first=Lee|date=December 18, 2019|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145533/https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/12/18/is-3m-stock-a-buy-for-2020.aspx|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> 3M's stock price closed at 256.01 on January 28, 2018, and by December 1, 2019, it had fallen to 168.27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/quote/nyse/3m/mmm/|title=News & Analysis: 3M|last=Nyitray|first=Brent|date=April 1, 2020|website=Fool|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145639/https://www.fool.com/quote/nyse/3m/mmm/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Satellite Awards]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[24th Satellite Awards|December 19, 2019]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actor, Drama]]\n| [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressacademy.com/2019-ipa-awards/|title=24th Satellite Awards nominations|date=2019|website=pressacademy.com|publisher=[[International Press Academy]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402145910/https://www.pressacademy.com/2019-ipa-awards/|archive-date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Mario Correa, [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], Nathaniel Rich\n| {{nom}}\n |-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Cinema for Peace]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 19th Cinema for Peace's Gala|February 23, 2020\n| Award for Justice 2020\n| [[Dark Waters]]\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020</ref>\n|-\n| International Green Film Award 2020\n| [[Dark Waters]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Perfluorinated alkylated substances]] (PFAS)\n* [[Timeline of events related to per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS)]]\n* ''[[The Devil We Know]]'' (2018 investigative documentary)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Todd Haynes}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s legal films]]\n[[Category:2010s mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films about lawyers]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Todd Haynes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Christine Vachon]]\n[[Category:Films set in Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Films set in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Films set in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1975]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1998]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2000]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2001]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2004]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2005]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2009]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2010]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2011]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2012]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2015]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Killer Films films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 American legal thriller film directed by Todd Haynes}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Dark Waters\n| image          = Dark Waters poster.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Todd Haynes]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n* [[Christine Vachon]]\n* Pamela Koffler\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* Mario Correa\n* [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n}}\n| based_on       = {{based on|\"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\"|[[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Ruffalo\n* [[Anne Hathaway]]\n* [[Tim Robbins]]\n* [[Bill Camp]]\n* [[Victor Garber]]\n* [[Mare Winningham]]\n* [[Bill Pullman]]\n}}<!--PER POSTER BILLING BLOCK-->\n| music          = [[Marcelo Zarvos]]\n| cinematography = [[Edward Lachman]]\n| editing        = [[Affonso Gon\u00e7alves]]\n| production companies         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Participant (company)|Participant]]\n* [[Killer Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Focus Features]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 126 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amctheatres.com/movies/dark-waters-61544 |title=Dark Waters |publisher=[[AMC Theatres]] |access-date=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $20 million\n| gross          = $21 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=darkwaters.htm |title=Dark Waters (2019) |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]. [[IMDb]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Dark Waters''''' is a 2019 American [[legal thriller]] film directed by [[Todd Haynes]] and written by Mario Correa and [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]]. The story dramatizes [[Robert Bilott]]'s case against the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]] after they contaminated a town with unregulated chemicals. It stars [[Mark Ruffalo]], [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]].\n\nThe film is based on the 2016 ''[[The New York Times Magazine|New York Times Magazine]]'' article \"The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare\" by [[Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|Nathaniel Rich]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/10/magazine/the-lawyer-who-became-duponts-worst-nightmare.html |title=The Lawyer Who Became DuPont's Worst Nightmare |last=Rich |first=Nathaniel |authorlink=Nathaniel Rich (novelist)|date=January 6, 2016|work=[[The New York Times Magazine]] |access-date=November 5, 2019 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/ |title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal |last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |date=January 9, 2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |language=en |url-status=live |access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> Parts of the story were also reported by Mariah Blake, whose 2015 article \"Welcome to Beautiful Parkersburg, West Virginia\" was a National Magazine Award finalist,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wwd.com/business-news/media/national-magazine-awards-ellies-asme-finalists-2016-revealed-10314630-10314630/ |title=American Society of Magazine Editors Unveils Finalists for 2016 National Magazine Awards |last=Steigrad|first=Alexandra|date=January 14, 2016|website=WWD |language=en |access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> and Sharon Lerner, whose series \"Bad Chemistry\" ran in ''[[The Intercept]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Sharon|last=Lerner|url=https://theintercept.com/collections/bad-chemistry/|title=Bad Chemistry |website=[[The Intercept]] |language=en|date=October 24, 2019|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2015/08/11/dupont-chemistry-deception/|title=The Teflon Toxin: DuPont and the Chemistry of Deception|last=Lerner|first=Sharon|date=August 11, 2015 |website=[[The Intercept]] |language=en-US|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Bilott also wrote a memoir, ''Exposure'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/exposurepoisoned0000bilo|title=Exposure: poisoned water, corporate greed, and one lawyer's twenty-year battle against DuPont |last=Bilott|first=Robert|date=2019 |location=New York |publisher=Atria Books |via=The Internet Archive}}</ref> detailing his 20-year legal battle against DuPont.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/9840cbc08c9048cc900f90bd1bd7fb4a|title=Lawyer who took on DuPont has book coming out |date=July 10, 2019|publisher=[[Associated Press]] |language=en-US|access-date=March 2, 2019}}</ref> \n\n''Dark Waters'' was theatrically released in a limited capacity on November 22, 2019, by [[Focus Features]], and went wide on December 6, 2019. The film received positive reviews from critics and has grossed $21 million.\n\n== Plot ==\n[[Robert Bilott]] is a corporate defense lawyer from [[Cincinnati, Ohio]] working for law firm [[Taft Stettinius & Hollister]]. Farmer Wilbur Tennant, who knows Robert's grandmother, asks Robert to investigate a number of unexplained deaths in [[Parkersburg, West Virginia]]. Tennant connects the deaths to the chemical manufacturing corporation [[DuPont (1802-2017)|DuPont]], and gives Robert a large case of videotapes.\n\nRobert visits the Tennants' farm, where he learns that 190 cattle have died with unusual medical conditions such as bloated organs, blackened teeth, and tumors. DuPont attorney Phil Donnelly tells him he is not aware of the case but will help out in any way he can. Robert files a small suit so he can gain information through [[legal discovery]] of the chemicals dumped on the site. When he finds nothing useful in the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|EPA]] report, he realizes the chemicals might not be regulated by the EPA.\n\nRobert confronts Phil at an industry event, leading to an angry exchange. DuPont sends Robert hundreds of boxes, hoping to bury the evidence. Robert finds numerous references to PFOA, a chemical with no references in any medical textbook. In the middle of the night, Robert's pregnant wife Sarah finds him tearing the carpet off the floors and going through their pans. He has discovered that PFOA is [[perfluorooctanoic acid]], used to manufacture [[Teflon]] and used in American homes for nonstick pans. DuPont has been running tests of the effect of PFOA for decades, finding that it causes cancer and birth defects, but did not make the findings public. They dumped hundreds of gallons of toxic sludge upriver from Tennant's farm. PFOA and similar compounds are [[Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances#Forever chemicals|forever chemicals]], chemicals that do not leave the blood stream [[Bioaccumulation|and slowly accumulate]].\n\nTennant has been shunned by the community for suing their biggest employer, and he and his wife both have cancer. Robert encourages him to accept DuPont's settlement, but Tennant refuses, wanting justice. He tells Robert he and his wife both have cancer. Robert sends the DuPont evidence to the EPA and Department of Justice, among others. The EPA fines DuPont $16.5 million.\n\nRobert, however, is not satisfied; he realizes that the residents of Parkersburg will suffer the effects of the PFOA for the rest of their lives. He seeks [[Monitoring (medicine)|medical monitoring]] for all residents of Parkersburg in one large [[Class action|class-action lawsuit]]. However, DuPont sends a letter notifying residents of the presence of PFOA, thus starting the [[statute of limitations]] and giving any further action only a month to begin.\n\nSince PFOA is not regulated, Robert's team argues that the corporation is liable, as the amount in the water was higher than the one part per billion deemed safe by DuPont's internal documents. In court, DuPont claims their later study found that 150 parts per billion is safe. The locals protest and the story becomes national news. DuPont agrees to settle for $70 million. As DuPont is only required to carry out medical monitoring if scientists prove that PFOA causes the ailments, an independent scientific review is set up. To get data for it, DuPont tells the locals they can get their settlement money after donating blood. Nearly 70,000 people donate to the study.\n\nSeven years pass with no result from the study. Tennant dies and Robert becomes destitute following several pay cuts, straining his marriage. When Tom tells him he needs to take another pay cut, Robert collapses, shaking. Doctors tell Sarah he suffered an [[ischemia]], brought on by stress. Sarah tells Tom to stop making Robert feel like a failure, since he is doing something for people who need help.\n\nThe scientific review contacts Robert and tells him that PFOA causes multiple cancers and other diseases. At dinner with his family, Robert is informed that DuPont is reneging on the entire agreement. Robert decides to take each defendant's case to DuPont, one at a time. He wins the first three multimillion-dollar settlements against DuPont, and DuPont settles the class action for $671 million.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{castlist|\n* [[Mark Ruffalo]] as [[Robert Bilott]]\n* [[Anne Hathaway]] as Sarah Bilott\n* [[Tim Robbins]] as Tom Terp\n* [[Bill Camp]] as Wilbur Tennant \n* [[Victor Garber]] as Phil Donnelly\n* [[Mare Winningham]] as Darlene Kiger\n* [[Bill Pullman]] as Harry Deitzler\n* [[William Jackson Harper]] as James Ross\n* [[Louisa Krause]] as Karla\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nOn September 21, 2018, it was announced that [[Todd Haynes]] would direct the film, then titled ''Dry Run'', from a script by [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], which would be produced by [[Participant (company)|Participant Media]] along with [[Mark Ruffalo]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/carol-todd-haynes-direct-dry-run-participant-media-1202469279/ |title='Carol' Helmer Todd Haynes To Direct 'Dry Run' Drama For Participant Media |last=N'Duka |first=Amanda |date=September 21, 2018  |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=September 22, 2018}}</ref> In November 2018, Ruffalo was officially set to star in the film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/mark-ruffalo-confirmed-participant-media-todd-haynes-dupont-drama-movie-1202498626/ |title=Mark Ruffalo To Star In Participant Media's Todd Haynes Pic About DuPont Pollution Scandal |last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |date=November 9, 2018|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |language=en |access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Anne Hathaway]], [[Tim Robbins]], [[Bill Camp]], [[Victor Garber]], [[Mare Winningham]], [[William Jackson Harper]], and [[Bill Pullman]] joined the cast of the film, with [[Christine Vachon]] and Pamela Koffler producing under their [[Killer Films]] banner.<ref name=\"MoreCast\">{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/anne-hathaway-tim-robbins-mark-ruffalo-todd-haynes-dupont-pollution-scandal-1202532048/ |title=Anne Hathaway, Tim Robbins, More Join Mark Ruffalo In Todd Haynes-Participant Drama About DuPont Pollution Scandal |last=Wiseman |first=Andreas |date=January 9, 2019 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] began on January 14, 2019, in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref name=\"MoreCast\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://local12.com/news/local/shooting-for-film-starring-mark-ruffalo-anne-hathaway-begins-in-hamilton-monday |title=Shooting for film starring Mark Ruffalo, Anne Hathaway begins in Hamilton Monday |date=January 11, 2019 |website=Local12.com |access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\nThe film was released in limited theatres on November 22, 2019, before going wide on December 6, 2019.<ref name=\"indiewire\">{{cite web|first=Tom|last=Brueggemann|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/11/box-office-dark-waters-arthouse-openers-1202191841/|title=\u2018Dark Waters\u2019 Leads Tepid Arthouse Openers at Crowded Box Office|website=[[Indiewire]]|date=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Dark Waters'' grossed $11.1 million in the United States and Canada, and $9.9 million in other countries, for a worldwide total of $21 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n\nIn its opening weekend the film made $102,656 from four theaters, a per-venue average of $25,651.<ref name=\"indiewire\"/> It expanded to 94 theaters the following weekend, making $630,000.<ref>{{cite web |last=Brueggemann |first=Tom |url= https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/holiday-box-office-harriet-jojo-rabbit-two-popes-1202193331/ |title= 'Harriet,' 'Jojo Rabbit,' and 'Parasite' Reap Holiday Box Office Bounty |website=[[IndieWire]] |date=December 1, 2019 |accessdate=December 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The film went wide in its third weekend of release, making $4.1 million from 2,012 theaters, and then made $1.9 million in its fourth weekend.<ref name=expand>{{cite web|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|title= \u2018Frozen 2\u2019 Leads Dreary December Weekend With $34M+, \u2018Playmobil\u2019 Plunges To $670K \u2013 Sunday Update |url= https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=December 8, 2019|date= December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/12/jumanji-the-next-level-richard-jewell-black-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202808689/ |title=\u2018Jumanji: The Next Level\u2019 Advancing To $51M+ Opening; \u2018Richard Jewell\u2019 & \u2018Black Christmas\u2019 Earn Lumps Of Coal |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 15, 2019 |accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 90% based on 197 reviews, with an average rating of 7.3/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''Dark Waters'' powerfully relays a real-life tale of infuriating malfeasance, honoring the victims and laying blame squarely at the feet of the perpetrators.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dark_waters_2019/|title=Dark Waters (2019)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 72 out of 100, based on 36 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/dark-waters|title=Dark Waters Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 3.5 out of 5 stars, with 60% saying they would definitely recommend it to a friend.<ref name=expand/>\n\n=== Economic response ===\nThe DowDuPont breakup earlier in the year spun off a new DuPont company that continued to lose value throughout the second half of 2019 as investors grew concerned about the potential liabilities related to the old DuPont's fluoropolymer products. When ''Dark Waters'' was released on November 12, DuPont's stock price dropped even further by 7.15 points from 72.18 to 65.03. While the portfolio is now a part of [[Chemours]] and the companies settled the public health lawsuits referenced in the film, Chemours sued DuPont, alleging that the former parent company saddled it with onerous liabilities when it failed to prepare financial projections in good faith. Chemours estimated that it would need to pay over $200 million to address environmental damages in North Carolina caused by another PFAS manufacturing facility in that region. (The prior settlement in both West Virginia and Ohio cost $671 million, which was split between the two companies.)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/01/09/heres-why-dupont-fell-405-in-2019.aspx |title= Here's Why DuPont Fell 40.5% in 2019 |website=fool.com |access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuPont CEO Marc Doyle, executives, and investors argued in internal statements that much of the movie was not based in fact and DuPont was misconstrued to fit the role of the enemy. According to Doyle, limited public statements were made because \u201cin a situation like this, it just doesn\u2019t do you much good to fight it out in the public eye. That would just drive more and more attention to it.\u201d Executive chairman Ed Breen wouldn\u2019t comment on whether DuPont would take legal action in response to the movie, but he did tell investors, \u201cObviously, we have a lot of legal folks [that] have been looking at this.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whyy.org/articles/dupont-execs-react-to-villain-role-in-dark-waters-film/ |title= DuPont execs react to villain role in \u2018Dark Waters\u2019 film |date=November 1, 2019 |website=whyy.org |access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> Many of the executives with whom this movie draws fault still work, or recently worked at DuPont. 3M saw little to no change in its stock price the day of the film's release, but it was already experiencing a \"difficult year\" from \"potential liabilities due to possible litigation over previous production of PFAS.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2019/12/18/is-3m-stock-a-buy-for-2020.aspx |title=Is 3M Stock a Buy for 2020? The industrial giant had a very difficult 2019, but is it set for a turnaround in the coming year? |date=December 18, 2019 |website=fool.com |access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref> 3M's stock price closed at 256.01 on January 28, 2018, and by December 1, 2019, it had fallen to 168.27.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fool.com/quote/nyse/3m/mmm/ |title=News & Analysis: 3M |website=fool.com |access-date=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| {{Abbr|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Satellite Awards]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[24th Satellite Awards|December 19, 2019]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actor, Drama]]\n| [[Mark Ruffalo]]\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressacademy.com/2019-ipa-awards/|title=24th Satellite Awards nominations|website=pressacademy.com|publisher=[[International Press Academy]]|accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]]\n| Mario Correa, [[Matthew Michael Carnahan]], Nathaniel Rich\n| {{nom}}\n |-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Cinema for Peace]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 19th Cinema for Peace's Gala|February 23, 2020\n| Award for Justice 2020\n| [[Dark Waters]]\n| {{nom}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2020</ref>\n|-\n| International Green Film Award 2020\n| [[Dark Waters]]\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Perfluorinated alkylated substances]] (PFAS)\n* [[Timeline of events related to per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS)]]\n* ''[[The Devil We Know]]'' (2018 investigative documentary)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Todd Haynes}}\n\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2010s legal films]]\n[[Category:2010s mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:Environmental films]]\n[[Category:Films about lawyers]]\n[[Category:Films based on newspaper and magazine articles]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Todd Haynes]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Matthew Michael Carnahan]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Christine Vachon]]\n[[Category:Films set in Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Films set in Delaware]]\n[[Category:Films set in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1975]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1998]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2000]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2001]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2002]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2003]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2004]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2005]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2009]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2010]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2011]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2012]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2015]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Focus Features films]]\n[[Category:Killer Films films]]\n", "name_user": "TipsyElephant", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added archive information for all references and added any available information to the reference metadata.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dark_Waters_(2019_film)"}
{"title_page": "Asian News International", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian news agency}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Asian News International\n| logo = File:Ani-logo-black.png\n| type = [[News agency]]\n| industry = [[Media (communication)|Media]], [[News media]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1971|12|09}} in [[New Delhi]], [[India]]<ref>{{cite web |title=ANI MEDIA PRIVATE LIMITED - Company, directors and contact details |url=https://www.zaubacorp.com/company/ANI-MEDIA-PRIVATE-LIMITED/U74899DL1971PTC005895 |website=zaubacorp.com |accessdate=22 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n| founder = Prem Prakash\n| hq_location_city = New Delhi\n| area_served = India, [[South Asia]]\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Sanjiv Prakash ([[Chief Executive Officer |CEO]])|Prem Prakash ([[Chairman]])}}\n| owner = ANI Media Private Limited<ref>{{cite web |title=Terms & Conditions |url=https://www.aninews.in/term-condition/ |website=aninews.in |language=en}}</ref>\n| parent = \n| website = {{URL|aninews.in}}\n}}\n\n'''Asian News International''' ('''ANI''') is an Indian news agency based in [[New Delhi]] that provides syndicated multimedia news feed to multiple news-bureaus in [[India]] and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MHujEBLJcvIC&pg=PA63|title=News Agencies from Pigeon to Internet|last1=Shrivastava|first1=K. M.|date=2007|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=9781932705676|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sVffFCoGSuIC&pg=PA122|title=International News in the 21st Century|last1=Paterson|first1=Chris A.|last2=Sreberny|first2=Annabelle|date=2004|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=9781860205965|page=122|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/footaging-it-fleetly/288837|title=Footaging It Fleetly|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Established by Prem Prakash, it was the first agency in India to syndicate video news.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YsJlAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA16|title=Web Journalism-The Craft & Technology|last1=Saxena|first1=Sunil|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=9780070680838|page=16|language=en}}</ref> {{As of|2019||df=}}, it is the biggest news agency in India; Smita Prakash is the Editor-in-Chief and is married to the CEO, Sanjiv Prakash.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Establishment and early years (1971-2000) ===\nPrem started his career in the field of photography, before being employed by [[Visnews]] (as well as [[Reuters]]) as a photojournalist, where he went on to cover some of the most significant historical events in post-Independence India.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/ani-reports-government-version-truth|title=The Image Makers : How ANI Reports The Government's Version Of Truth|last=Donthi|first=Praveen|date=1 March 2019|website=[[The Caravan]]|language=en|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://the-ken.com/story/ani-video-news-monopoly/|title=How ANI quietly built a monopoly|last=Ahluwalia|first=Harveen|last2=Srivilasan|first2=Pranav|date=2018-10-21|website=The Ken|language=en-US|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> He was a significant figure in the domain of news and documentary film-making in the 1970s\u2014commanding considerable clout among foreign journalists and film-makers\u2014and had been conferred with the [[MBE]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nANI was established in 1971 (preceded by TVNF, which was India\u2019s first television news feature agency) and leveraged a host of tactics from the employing of numerous ex-bureaucrats (along with their kith and kin) at prime positions to cordialising his familial connections with [[I. K. Gujral]], (the then minister of Information and Broadcasting) in a quest to gain influence within the Government.<ref name=\":0\" /> TVNF was explicitly asked by [[Indira Gandhi]] to showcase a positive image of India, and monopolized the sector, producing numerous science-oriented films for [[Doordarshan]], the state broadcaster.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSmita Prakash, an alumna of [[Indian Institute of Mass Communication]] joined ANI in around 1986 as an intern and was later inducted as a full-time employee.<ref name=\":0\" /> Daughter of Inna Ramamohan Rao, former director of the [[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)|Ministry of Information and Broadcasting]], she married Prem's son Sanjiv in 1988 and furthered ANI's access within the government.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> For years along, ANI effectively served as an external publicity division of [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]], showing the Army in a positive light and suppressing news about any internal discontent; the private nature of the organisation gave an air of non-partisan legitimacy to their videos.<ref name=\":0\" /> During the peak-spans of militancy in [[Kashmir conflict|Kashmir Conflict]], ANI was the near-sole purveyor of video-footage, esp. with Rao having been recruited as the media advisor to the state.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1993, Reuters purchased a stake in ANI, which was allowed to exert a complete monopoly over the Reuters feed; Prem's connections with [[Peter Job]] helped the cause.<ref name=\":0\" /> Also, along the 90s, Sanjiv had a meteoric rise through the ranks (along with Smita) and his shrewd managerial instincts increasingly divorced journalism from the organisation's goals.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Later years (2000-present) ===\nBy 2000, India had seen a boom of private 24X7 news channels; however, unsustainable revenue models meant that they did not have the capacity to hire video-reporters across the country.<ref name=\":0\" /> Coupled with [[Bharatiya Janata Party|Bhartiya Janata Party]]'s ascendancy to power, it provided the scope for a massive expansion of ANI's domestic video-production capacities.<ref name=\":0\" /> Asian Films TV was incorporated in 2000 to provide feed for newspapers and periodicals.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, most of its foot-soldiers were low-cost recruits, who had little to do with journalism.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2000, the [[National Democratic Alliance|NDA]] government launched a Kashmir based regional channel\u2014[[DD Kashir]] and ANI was allowed to produce its programs;<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> By the end of 2005, ANI's business-model was performing impressively and it had shifted its office out of Gole Market, to a new five-storey building in [[Rama Krishna Puram|R.K. Puram]].<ref name=\":0\" /> ANI continued to be trusted by the upcoming [[United Progressive Alliance|UPA]] governments, to the extent of MEA choosing Smita to be a part of the two-member-strong contingent of Indian journalists at both of the joint press conferences between the incumbent prime ministers of India and USA.<ref name=\":0\" /> ANI is also believed to have played significant roles as allies of the [[Research and Analysis Wing]], India's external intelligence agency; many of its videos depicted protests by lobby groups and fringe activists, across the world, on the aspects of human rights abuse in Pakistan.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nPost 2005, news channels started unsubscribing from ANI due to increasing charges and low quality of journalism, coupled with the introduction of [[Outside broadcasting|broadcast vans]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2010, UNI TV was launched by [[Yashwant Deshmukh]] as a competitor and gave stiff competition.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, Ishan Prakash, Smita's son joined the company in 2011 and procured multiple units of [[LiveU]], a pioneer technology that were an advancement over OB vans and far more portable.<ref name=\":0\" /> The agency also expanded its overseas bureaus and enlisted into contracts with multiple state governments and multiple union ministries.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> A monopoly was again re-created and most of its competitors shut down, eventually.<ref name=\":0\" /> By late 2011, ANI accounted for about 99% of the Reuters feed and in FY 2017-18, they were paid \u20b9 2.54 crore for the services.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nUnder a new management, ANI has been accused of practicing an even-aggressive journalism model focused at maximum revenue output, but where journalists are easily dispensable with.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Archive videos were sold at rates as high as \u20b9 1000 per second; in FY 2017-18, the firm reported revenues of \u20b9 68.23 crore and a net profit of \u20b9 9.91 crore.<ref name=\":1\" /> Multiple employees have accused ANI of not having any human resource management, in place and ill-treating their ex-employees.<ref name=\":0\" /> ; the effects have ranged from covering the party-campaigns to the farthest possible extent to reporters being highly pro-active, when dealing with politicians from opposition parties.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Smita has been widely accused of conducting favorable interviews for the party.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/05/indian-pm-narendra-modi-lampooned-for-manufactured-interview|title=Indian PM lampooned for 'manufactured' interview|last=Dhillon|first=Amrit|date=2019-01-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nANI has been also documented to be a significant purveyor of [[Fake news in India|fake news]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/ani-a-tale-of-inadvertent-errors-and-oversights/|title=ANI - A tale of inadvertent errors and oversights|last=Chaudhuri|first=Pooja|date=2018-10-21|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> The Caravan noted several video footage from the unit, wherein logos of random television channels from Pakistan along with Urdu tickers were superimposed on news showcasing India in a positive light; video editors admitted to forging clips.<ref name=\":0\" /> Long-form reports by [[The Caravan]] and [[The Ken]], along with reports by media watchdogs  have covered about how the agency has served as an effective propaganda tool of the incumbent union governments, across the years.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newslaundry.com/2019/09/18/ani-news-european-experts-kashmir|title=Meet ANI\u2019s \u2018European experts\u2019 on Kashmir. They're experts all right \u2014 just not on Kashmir|last=Tiwari|first=Ayush|date=18 September 2019|website=Newslaundry|url-status=live|access-date=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n==Criticism and controversy==\n\n===Peddling Indian government Agenda===\nANI has been caught peddling the Indian govt agenda multiple times. On April 12th ANI manufactured a news report claiming that veterans had denied writing a letter to President [[Ram Nath Kovind]] but the veterans denied any such thing and complained to [[Reuters]] against this unethical practice.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web |title=Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/veterans-write-to-reuters-about-ani-s-report/cid/1689378}}</ref>\n\n===Using ruling party members to interview as General public===\nANI has multiple times used people belonging to the ruling party or affiliated with the ruling party [[BJP]] to pass them off as eyewitnesses or general public.<ref name=\"Altnews\">{{cite web |title=Altnews|url=https://www.altnews.in/ani-a-tale-of-inadvertent-errors-and-oversights/}}</ref>\n\n\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Press Trust of India]], the other leading news agency based in India.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{News agencies}}\n\n[[Category:Multilingual news services]]\n[[Category:News agencies based in India]]\n[[Category:Indian companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Delhi]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian news agency}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Asian News International\n| logo = File:Ani-logo-black.png\n| type = [[News agency]]\n| industry = [[Media (communication)|Media]], [[News media]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1971|12|09}} in [[New Delhi]], [[India]]<ref>{{cite web |title=ANI MEDIA PRIVATE LIMITED - Company, directors and contact details |url=https://www.zaubacorp.com/company/ANI-MEDIA-PRIVATE-LIMITED/U74899DL1971PTC005895 |website=zaubacorp.com |accessdate=22 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n| founder = Prem Prakash\n| hq_location_city = New Delhi\n| area_served = India, [[South Asia]]\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Sanjiv Prakash ([[Chief Executive Officer |CEO]])|Prem Prakash ([[Chairman]])}}\n| owner = ANI Media Private Limited<ref>{{cite web |title=Terms & Conditions |url=https://www.aninews.in/term-condition/ |website=aninews.in |language=en}}</ref>\n| parent = \n| website = {{URL|aninews.in}}\n}}\n\n'''Asian News International''' ('''ANI''') is an Indian news agency based in [[New Delhi]] that provides syndicated multimedia news feed to multiple news-bureaus in [[India]] and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MHujEBLJcvIC&pg=PA63|title=News Agencies from Pigeon to Internet|last1=Shrivastava|first1=K. M.|date=2007|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|isbn=9781932705676|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sVffFCoGSuIC&pg=PA122|title=International News in the 21st Century|last1=Paterson|first1=Chris A.|last2=Sreberny|first2=Annabelle|date=2004|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=9781860205965|page=122|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/footaging-it-fleetly/288837|title=Footaging It Fleetly|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> Established by Prem Prakash, it was the first agency in India to syndicate video news.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YsJlAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA16|title=Web Journalism-The Craft & Technology|last1=Saxena|first1=Sunil|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education|isbn=9780070680838|page=16|language=en}}</ref> {{As of|2019||df=}}, it is the biggest news agency in India; Smita Prakash is the Editor-in-Chief and is married to the CEO, Sanjiv Prakash.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Establishment and early years (1971-2000) ===\nPrem started his career in the field of photography, before being employed by [[Visnews]] (as well as [[Reuters]]) as a photojournalist, where he went on to cover some of the most significant historical events in post-Independence India.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://caravanmagazine.in/reportage/ani-reports-government-version-truth|title=The Image Makers : How ANI Reports The Government's Version Of Truth|last=Donthi|first=Praveen|date=1 March 2019|website=[[The Caravan]]|language=en|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://the-ken.com/story/ani-video-news-monopoly/|title=How ANI quietly built a monopoly|last=Ahluwalia|first=Harveen|last2=Srivilasan|first2=Pranav|date=2018-10-21|website=The Ken|language=en-US|url-access=subscription|url-status=live|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> He was a significant figure in the domain of news and documentary film-making in the 1970s\u2014commanding considerable clout among foreign journalists and film-makers\u2014and had been conferred with the [[MBE]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nANI was established in 1971 (preceded by TVNF, which was India\u2019s first television news feature agency) and leveraged a host of tactics from the employing of numerous ex-bureaucrats (along with their kith and kin) at prime positions to cordialising his familial connections with [[I. K. Gujral]], (the then minister of Information and Broadcasting) in a quest to gain influence within the Government.<ref name=\":0\" /> TVNF was explicitly asked by [[Indira Gandhi]] to showcase a positive image of India, and monopolized the sector, producing numerous science-oriented films for [[Doordarshan]], the state broadcaster.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nSmita Prakash, an alumna of [[Indian Institute of Mass Communication]] joined ANI in around 1986 as an intern and was later inducted as a full-time employee.<ref name=\":0\" /> Daughter of Inna Ramamohan Rao, former director of the [[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)|Ministry of Information and Broadcasting]], she married Prem's son Sanjiv in 1988 and furthered ANI's access within the government.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> For years along, ANI effectively served as an external publicity division of [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]], showing the Army in a positive light and suppressing news about any internal discontent; the private nature of the organisation gave an air of non-partisan legitimacy to their videos.<ref name=\":0\" /> During the peak-spans of militancy in [[Kashmir conflict|Kashmir Conflict]], ANI was the near-sole purveyor of video-footage, esp. with Rao having been recruited as the media advisor to the state.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1993, Reuters purchased a stake in ANI, which was allowed to exert a complete monopoly over the Reuters feed; Prem's connections with [[Peter Job]] helped the cause.<ref name=\":0\" /> Also, along the 90s, Sanjiv had a meteoric rise through the ranks (along with Smita) and his shrewd managerial instincts increasingly divorced journalism from the organisation's goals.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Later years (2000-present) ===\nBy 2000, India had seen a boom of private 24X7 news channels; however, unsustainable revenue models meant that they did not have the capacity to hire video-reporters across the country.<ref name=\":0\" /> Coupled with [[Bharatiya Janata Party|Bhartiya Janata Party]]'s ascendancy to power, it provided the scope for a massive expansion of ANI's domestic video-production capacities.<ref name=\":0\" /> Asian Films TV was incorporated in 2000 to provide feed for newspapers and periodicals.<ref name=\":1\" /> However, most of its foot-soldiers were low-cost recruits, who had little to do with journalism.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2000, the [[National Democratic Alliance|NDA]] government launched a Kashmir based regional channel\u2014[[DD Kashir]] and ANI was allowed to produce its programs;<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> By the end of 2005, ANI's business-model was performing impressively and it had shifted its office out of Gole Market, to a new five-storey building in [[Rama Krishna Puram|R.K. Puram]].<ref name=\":0\" /> ANI continued to be trusted by the upcoming [[United Progressive Alliance|UPA]] governments, to the extent of MEA choosing Smita to be a part of the two-member-strong contingent of Indian journalists at both of the joint press conferences between the incumbent prime ministers of India and USA.<ref name=\":0\" /> ANI is also believed to have played significant roles as allies of the [[Research and Analysis Wing]], India's external intelligence agency; many of its videos depicted protests by lobby groups and fringe activists, across the world, on the aspects of human rights abuse in Pakistan.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nPost 2005, news channels started unsubscribing from ANI due to increasing charges and low quality of journalism, coupled with the introduction of [[Outside broadcasting|broadcast vans]].<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2010, UNI TV was launched by [[Yashwant Deshmukh]] as a competitor and gave stiff competition.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, Ishan Prakash, Smita's son joined the company in 2011 and procured multiple units of [[LiveU]], a pioneer technology that were an advancement over OB vans and far more portable.<ref name=\":0\" /> The agency also expanded its overseas bureaus and enlisted into contracts with multiple state governments and multiple union ministries.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> A monopoly was again re-created and most of its competitors shut down, eventually.<ref name=\":0\" /> By late 2011, ANI accounted for about 99% of the Reuters feed and in FY 2017-18, they were paid \u20b9 2.54 crore for the services.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nUnder a new management, ANI has been accused of practicing an even-aggressive journalism model focused at maximum revenue output, but where journalists are easily dispensable with.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Archive videos were sold at rates as high as \u20b9 1000 per second; in FY 2017-18, the firm reported revenues of \u20b9 68.23 crore and a net profit of \u20b9 9.91 crore.<ref name=\":1\" /> Multiple employees have accused ANI of not having any human resource management, in place and ill-treating their ex-employees.<ref name=\":0\" /> ; the effects have ranged from covering the party-campaigns to the farthest possible extent to reporters being highly pro-active, when dealing with politicians from opposition parties.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> Smita has been widely accused of conducting favorable interviews for the party.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/05/indian-pm-narendra-modi-lampooned-for-manufactured-interview|title=Indian PM lampooned for 'manufactured' interview|last=Dhillon|first=Amrit|date=2019-01-05|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n\nANI has been also documented to be a significant purveyor of [[Fake news in India|fake news]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altnews.in/ani-a-tale-of-inadvertent-errors-and-oversights/|title=ANI - A tale of inadvertent errors and oversights|last=Chaudhuri|first=Pooja|date=2018-10-21|website=Alt News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref> The Caravan noted several video footage from the unit, wherein logos of random television channels from Pakistan along with Urdu tickers were superimposed on news showcasing India in a positive light; video editors admitted to forging clips.<ref name=\":0\" /> Long-form reports by [[The Caravan]] and [[The Ken]], along with reports by media watchdogs  have covered about how the agency has served as an effective propaganda tool of the incumbent union governments, across the years.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newslaundry.com/2019/09/18/ani-news-european-experts-kashmir|title=Meet ANI\u2019s \u2018European experts\u2019 on Kashmir. They're experts all right \u2014 just not on Kashmir|last=Tiwari|first=Ayush|date=18 September 2019|website=Newslaundry|url-status=live|access-date=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n==Criticism and controversy==\n\n===Peddling Indian government Agenda===\nANI has been caught peddling the Indian govt agenda multiple times. On April 12th ANI manufactured a news report claiming that veterans had denied writing a letter to President [[Ram Nath Kovind]] but the veterans denied any such thing and complained to [[Reuters]] against this unethical practice. <ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web |title=Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/veterans-write-to-reuters-about-ani-s-report/cid/1689378}}</ref>\n\n===Using ruling party members to interview as General public===\nANI has multiple times used people belonging to the ruling party or affiliated with the ruling party [[BJP]] to pass them off as eyewitnesses or general public. <ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web |title=Altnews|url=https://www.altnews.in/ani-a-tale-of-inadvertent-errors-and-oversights/}}</ref>\n\n\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Press Trust of India]], the other leading news agency based in India.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{News agencies}}\n\n[[Category:Multilingual news services]]\n[[Category:News agencies based in India]]\n[[Category:Indian companies established in 1971]]\n[[Category:Companies based in New Delhi]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asian_News_International"}
